\description{
Audit how much excess loss was contributed and received across portfolio
segments after \code{\link[=redistribute_excess_loss]{redistribute_excess_loss()}}. The summary shows whether a
segment receives more large-loss cost than it contributes, or transfers part
of its observed excess burden to other segments. The same audit is available
for redistributed claims and separate excess loadings.
}
\details{
\code{redistributed_excess_contributed} is the excess amount removed from selected
large losses in a segment. \code{redistributed_excess_received} is the amount
assigned back to claim-bearing rows in that segment. Their difference is:

\deqn{
net\_loss\_shift = received - contributed
}

A positive value means that the segment receives more redistributed loss
than it contributed. A negative value means that it transfers loss to other
segments. Across the full portfolio, \code{net_loss_shift} sums to zero, subject
to numerical tolerance.

When \code{by = NULL}, the summary uses the \code{risk_factor} supplied to
\code{\link[=redistribute_excess_loss]{redistribute_excess_loss()}}. If no risk factor was supplied, one portfolio
row is returned. Supply \code{by} to inspect a portfolio redistribution by another
portfolio characteristic, for example \code{summary(x, by = "sector")}.

The summary also exposes the loading calculation. For partial
redistribution, \verb{<risk_factor>_excess_loading} is blended with
\code{portfolio_excess_loading} using \verb{<risk_factor>_credibility}. The resulting
\code{blended_excess_loading} is multiplied by
\code{redistribution_scaling_factor} to obtain
\code{final_redistribution_loading}. Multiplying the final loading by the total
receiving \code{redistribution_weight} gives
\code{redistributed_excess_received}.

If \code{by} differs from the risk factor used in the redistribution, loading and
credibility columns are receiving-weighted averages within each audit group.
For separate-loading output, \code{adjusted_loss} is shown only as a reconciliation
of retained plus allocated loss; it does not mean that the allocated amount
was added to the row-level severity response.
